{
  "query": "In European grasslands, how does post-seeding management by mowing compare to livestock grazing for enhancing sown species?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across European studies, mowing after sowing increased the richness of sown species and increased overall plant species richness compared to livestock grazing, and mowing also increased the abundance of sown forb species, with more frequent mowing boosting the abundance of five of seven sown forb species [3419]. A UK comparison found that grazing after sowing reduced plant species richness relative to cutting after sowing [3423]. Under grazing, European studies reported mixed or neutral effects on sown/target species abundance: grazing in Hungary did not change target species cover compared to no grazing, and in the UK cattle grazing reduced sown species cover compared to sheep grazing [3423]. Additionally, within mowing regimes, cutting annually and removing cut vegetation increased sown grass and forb richness, but removing cut vegetation reduced the cover of sown species compared to leaving cuttings in place [3419].",
